The 15-member United Nations Security Council today voted 13-0 to approve a  resolution imposing broad trade and military sanctions on Iraq.
Cuba and Yemen  abstained.
Sanctions are legally binding on all member nations, but past resolutions have  often been ignored or brazenly violated.
United States.
Japan and the European  Community had already imposed sanctions.
The Soviet Union and China halted arms  shipments to Iraq.
The Iraqi-installed Provisional Government of Kuwait issued a not so subtle warning on  Sunday, telling countries that tried to punish Iraq that they would be jeopardizing their  interest and nationals in Kuwait. 
